  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "America is divided into how many classes of people?",
  "response": "Sociologists and economists often categorize American society into different classes based on income, wealth, education, and occupation. While there isn't a universally agreed-upon number of classes, a common model divides America into three main classes:\n\n1. **Upper Class**: This includes the wealthiest individuals and families, often characterized by significant wealth, high income, and influential positions in society. This class can be further divided into the \"old money\" elite and the \"new money\" affluent.\n\n2. **Middle Class**: This is a broad category that includes a wide range of incomes and occupations. It is often subdivided into the upper-middle class, middle class, and lower-middle class. The middle class typically includes professionals, managers, and skilled workers.\n\n3. **Lower Class** (or Working Class and Poor): This class includes those with lower incomes and fewer resources. It encompasses working-class individuals who may hold low-wage jobs, as well as those living in poverty.\n\nSome models also include additional classes, such as:\n\n- **Working Class**: Often considered a subset of the lower class, this group includes people who are employed but earn wages that are at or near the poverty line.\n- **Underclass**: This term is sometimes used to describe those who are persistently poor and may face significant barriers to social mobility.\n\nThe exact delineation of these classes can vary based on the criteria used and the perspective of the researcher or organization defining them.",
